					<tbody>
						<tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">1</div> <div class="vers-content">Et surrexit Judas, qui vocabatur Machabæus, filius ejus, pro eo:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">1</div> <div class="vers-content">Then  his son Judas, called Machabeus, rose up in his stead.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">1</div> <div class="vers-content">And now his son Judas, that was called Machabaeus, came forward to succeed him;</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">2</div> <div class="vers-content">et adjuvabant eum omnes fratres ejus, et universi qui se conjunxerant patri ejus, et præliabantur prælium Israël cum lætitia.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">2</div> <div class="vers-content">And all his brethren helped him, and all they that had joined themselves to his father, and they fought with cheerfulness the battle of Israel.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">2</div> <div class="vers-content">nor any of Judas’ clan, nor any that had taken his father’s part, but lent him their aid still; right merrily they fought Israel’s battle.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">3</div> <div class="vers-content">Et dilatavit gloriam populo suo, et induit se loricam sicut gigas, et succinxit se arma bellica sua in præliis, et protegebat castra gladio suo.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">3</div> <div class="vers-content">And he got his people great honour, and put on a breastplate as a giant, and girt his warlike armour about him in battles, and protected the camp with his sword.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">3</div> <div class="vers-content">Here was one that brought his race renown; as great a warrior as ever donned breastplate, or armed himself for the fight, or drew sword to save his camp from peril;</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">4</div> <div class="vers-content">Similis factus est leoni in operibus suis, et sicut catulus leonis rugiens in venatione.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">4</div> <div class="vers-content">In his acts he was like a lion, and like a lion’s whelp roaring for his prey.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">4</div> <div class="vers-content">lion-hearted his deeds, not lion itself more relentless in pursuit.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">5</div> <div class="vers-content">Et persecutus est iniquos perscrutans eos: et qui conturbabant populum suum, eos succendit flammis:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">5</div> <div class="vers-content">And he pursued the wicked and sought them out, and them that troubled his people he burnt with fire:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">5</div> <div class="vers-content">Traitors he ever sought out and hunted down, ever with fire-brand the oppressors of his people dislodged,</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">6</div> <div class="vers-content">et repulsi sunt inimici ejus præ timore ejus, et omnes operarii iniquitatis conturbati sunt: et directa est salus in manu ejus.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">6</div> <div class="vers-content">And his enemies were driven away for fear of him, and all the workers of iniquity were troubled: and salvation prospered in his hand.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">6</div> <div class="vers-content">till enemy was none but was daunted by the fear of him, traitor was none but fled in confusion, so well sped he the work of deliverance.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">7</div> <div class="vers-content">Et exacerbabat reges multos, et lætificabat Jacob in operibus suis, et in sæculum memoria ejus in benedictione.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">7</div> <div class="vers-content">And he grieved many kings, and made Jacob glad with his works, and his memory is blessed for ever.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">7</div> <div class="vers-content">Great deeds, that kings rued bitterly, Jacob with exultation heard, posterity holds blessed evermore!</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">8</div> <div class="vers-content">Et perambulavit civitates Juda, et perdidit impios ex eis, et avertit iram ab Israël.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">8</div> <div class="vers-content">And he went through the cities of Juda, and destroyed the wicked out of them, and turned away wrath from Israel.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">8</div> <div class="vers-content">From city to city he went, ridding Juda of its law-breakers, averting the vengeance guilt of theirs had deserved;</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">9</div> <div class="vers-content">Et nominatus est usque ad novissimum terræ, et congregavit pereuntes.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">9</div> <div class="vers-content">And he was renowned even to the utmost part of the earth, and he gathered them that were perishing.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">9</div> <div class="vers-content">no corner of earth but he was renowned there, for one that had been able to rally a doomed people.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">10</div> <div class="vers-content">Et congregavit Apollonius gentes, et a Samaria virtutem multam et magnam ad bellandum contra Israël.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">10</div> <div class="vers-content">And Apollonius gathered together the Gentiles, and a numerous and great army from Samaria, to make war against Israel.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">10</div> <div class="vers-content">How sped Apollonius, that mustered a great force, of Gentiles and Samaritans both, to fight against Israel?</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">11</div> <div class="vers-content">Et cognovit Judas, et exiit obviam illi: et percussit, et occidit illum: et ceciderunt vulnerati multi, et reliqui fugerunt.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">11</div> <div class="vers-content">And Judas understood it, and went forth to meet him: and he overthrew him, and killed him: and many fell down slain, and the rest fled away.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">11</div> <div class="vers-content">No sooner Judas heard of it, than he met and routed and slew him; fell many and fled more,</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">12</div> <div class="vers-content">Et accepit spolia eorum: et gladium Apollonii abstulit Judas, et erat pugnans in eo omnibus diebus.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">12</div> <div class="vers-content">And he took their spoils, and Judas took the sword of Apollonius, and fought with it all his lifetime.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">12</div> <div class="vers-content">leaving their spoils behind them. The sword of Apollonius Judas himself carried away; and this it was he evermore used in battle.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">13</div> <div class="vers-content">Et audivit Seron princeps exercitus Syriæ, quod congregavit Judas congregationem fidelium, et ecclesiam secum,</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">13</div> <div class="vers-content">And Seron captain of the army of Syria heard that Judas had assembled a company of the faithful, and a congregation with him,</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">13</div> <div class="vers-content">And next it was Seron, captain of the armies in Syria, heard what a great retinue and faithful following Judas had;</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">14</div> <div class="vers-content">et ait: Faciam mihi nomen, et glorificabor in regno, et debellabo Judam, et eos qui cum ipso sunt, qui spernebant verbum regis.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">14</div> <div class="vers-content">And he said: I will get me a name, and will be glorified in the kingdom, and will overthrow Judas, and those that are with him, that have despised the edict of the king.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">14</div> <div class="vers-content">and nothing would serve, but he must win renown and high favour at court by crushing Judas, and all other his companions that defied the king’s edict.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">15</div> <div class="vers-content">Et præparavit se: et ascenderunt cum eo castra impiorum fortes auxiliarii ut facerent vindictam in filios Israël.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">15</div> <div class="vers-content">And he made himself ready: and the host of the wicked went up with him, strong succours, to be revenged of the children of Israel.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">15</div> <div class="vers-content">So he made all ready, and marched in with a strong muster of the ungodly at his heels, to be even with the men of Israel.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">16</div> <div class="vers-content">Et appropinquaverunt usque ad Bethoron: et exivit Judas obviam illi cum paucis.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">16</div> <div class="vers-content">And they approached even as far as Bethoron: and Judas went forth to meet him, with a small company.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">16</div> <div class="vers-content">As far as Bethoron pass they reached, and there Judas met them with his company, no better than a handful.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">17</div> <div class="vers-content">Ut autem viderunt exercitum venientem sibi obviam, dixerunt Judæ: Quomodo poterimus pauci pugnare contra multitudinem tantam, et tam fortem, et nos fatigati sumus jejunio hodie?</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">17</div> <div class="vers-content">But when they saw the army coming to meet them, they said to Judas: How shall we, being few, be able to fight against so great a multitude and so strong, and we are ready to faint with fasting to day?</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">17</div> <div class="vers-content">These, when they saw such a host facing them, were for counsels of prudence; What, they said to Judas, should we offer battle to foes so many and so strong, faint as we be from a day of hungry marching?</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">18</div> <div class="vers-content">Et ait Judas: Facile est concludi multos in manus paucorum: et non est differentia in conspectu Dei cæli liberare in multis, et in paucis:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">18</div> <div class="vers-content">And Judas said: It is an easy matter for many to be shut up in the hands of a few: and there is no difference in the sight of the God of heaven to deliver with a great multitude, or with a small company:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">18</div> <div class="vers-content">Nay, said Judas, nothing forbids great numbers should be at the mercy of small; what matter makes it to the God of heaven, few be his soldiers or many when he grants deliverance?</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">19</div> <div class="vers-content">quoniam non in multitudine exercitus victoria belli, sed de cælo fortitudo est.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">19</div> <div class="vers-content">For the success of war is not in the multitude of the army, but strength cometh from heaven.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">19</div> <div class="vers-content">Armed might avails not to win the day; victory is from above.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">20</div> <div class="vers-content">Ipsi veniunt ad nos in multitudine contumaci, et superbia, ut disperdant nos, et uxores nostras, et filios nostros, et ut spolient nos:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">20</div> <div class="vers-content">They come against us with an insolent multitude, and with pride, to destroy us, and our wives, and our children, and to take our spoils.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">20</div> <div class="vers-content">What though they come to meet us in the proud confidence of superior strength, and think it an easy matter to slay us, slay our wives and children, plunder our goods?</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">21</div> <div class="vers-content">nos vero pugnabimus pro animabus nostris, et legibus nostris:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">21</div> <div class="vers-content">But we will fight for our lives and our laws:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">21</div> <div class="vers-content">Life and loyalty at stake, we will offer battle none the less;</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">22</div> <div class="vers-content">et ipse Dominus conteret eos ante faciem nostram: vos autem ne timueritis eos.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">22</div> <div class="vers-content">And the Lord himself will overthrow them before our face: but as for you, fear them not.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">22</div> <div class="vers-content">and he, the Lord, will crush them to earth at our coming; never be afraid.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">23</div> <div class="vers-content">Ut cessavit autem loqui, insiluit in eos subito: et contritus est Seron et exercitus ejus in conspectu ipsius:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">23</div> <div class="vers-content">And as soon as he had made an end of speaking, he rushed suddenly upon them: and Seron and his host were overthrown before him:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">23</div> <div class="vers-content">And with that, all unawares, he fell upon Seron and his army, that were crushed, sure enough, by his onslaught;</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">24</div> <div class="vers-content">et persecutus est eum in descensu Bethoron usque in campum, et ceciderunt ex eis octingenti viri, reliqui autem fugerunt in terram Philisthiim.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">24</div> <div class="vers-content">And he pursued him by the descent of Bethoron even to the plain, and there fell of them eight hundred men, and the rest fled into the land of the Philistines.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">24</div> <div class="vers-content">all down the pass of Bethoron he gave them chase, down into the plain, and eight hundred of them had fallen before ever they took refuge in the country of the Philistines.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">25</div> <div class="vers-content">Et cecidit timor Judæ ac fratrum ejus, et formido super omnes gentes in circuitu eorum:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">25</div> <div class="vers-content">And the fear of Judas and of his brethren, and the dread of them fell upon all the nations round about them.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">25</div> <div class="vers-content">By this, the neighbouring peoples had begun to take alarm, so formidable did Judas and his brethren appear to them,</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">26</div> <div class="vers-content">et pervenit ad regem nomen ejus, et de præliis Judæ narrabant omnes gentes.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">26</div> <div class="vers-content">And his fame came to the king, and all nations told of the battles of Judas.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">26</div> <div class="vers-content">and the renown of him reached the king’s court; all the world was talking of Judas and his victories.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">27</div> <div class="vers-content">Ut audivit autem rex Antiochus sermones istos, iratus est animo: et misit, et congregavit exercitum universi regni sui, castra fortia valde:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">27</div> <div class="vers-content">Now when king Antiochus heard these words, he was angry in his mind: and he sent and gathered the forces of all his kingdom, an exceeding strong army.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">27</div> <div class="vers-content">An angry man was king Antiochus when the news came to him; he sent word round, and had all his army summoned together, a brave array, be sure of it.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">28</div> <div class="vers-content">et aperuit ærarium suum, et dedit stipendia exercitui in annum: et mandavit illis ut essent parati ad omnia.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">28</div> <div class="vers-content">And he opened his treasury, and gave out pay to the army for a year: and he commanded them, that they should be ready for all things.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">28</div> <div class="vers-content">The treasury must be opened, to provide the troops with a whole year’s pay, and keep them in readiness for every need.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">29</div> <div class="vers-content">Et vidit quod defecit pecunia de thesauris suis, et tributa regionis modica propter dissensionem et plagam quam fecit in terra, ut tolleret legitima, quæ erant a primis diebus:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">29</div> <div class="vers-content">And he perceived that the money of his treasures failed, and that the tributes of the country were small because of the dissension, and the evil that he had brought upon the land, that he might take away the laws of old times:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">29</div> <div class="vers-content">Why, what was this? So heavily had Juda suffered, so great the discord he had aroused by the abolishing of its ancient usages, that scant revenue had come in from it, and the treasury was in default!</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">30</div> <div class="vers-content">et timuit ne non haberet ut semel et bis, in sumptus et donaria, quæ dederat ante larga manu: et abundaverat super reges qui ante eum fuerant.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">30</div> <div class="vers-content">And he feared that he should not have as formerly enough, for charges and gifts, which he had given before with a liberal hand: for he had abounded more than the kings that had been before him.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">30</div> <div class="vers-content">Whence, now, to defray the cost of that largesse he had made so often, and with so lavish a hand? Never was king before him could rival his munificence.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">31</div> <div class="vers-content">Et consternatus erat animo valde, et cogitavit ire in Persidem, et accipere tributa regionum, et congregare argentum multum.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">31</div> <div class="vers-content">And he was greatly perplexed in mind, and purposed to go into Persia, and to take tributes of the countries, and to gather much money.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">31</div> <div class="vers-content">Here was the king in great confusion of mind; and his thought was, to march into Persia and take toll of those countries; great store of money he might there amass.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">32</div> <div class="vers-content">Et reliquit Lysiam hominem nobilem de genere regali, super negotia regia, a flumine Euphrate usque ad flumen Ægypti,</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">32</div> <div class="vers-content">And he left Lysias, a nobleman of the blood royal, to oversee the affairs of the kingdom, from the river Euphrates even to the river of Egypt:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">32</div> <div class="vers-content">He left Lysias behind, that was a man of high rank and royal blood; he was to administer all the business of the kingdom, from Euphrates down to the Brook of Egypt,</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">33</div> <div class="vers-content">et ut nutriret Antiochum filium suum, donec rediret.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">33</div> <div class="vers-content">And to bring up his son Antiochus, till he came again.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">33</div> <div class="vers-content">and have charge of the young prince Antiochus, until the king’s return.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">34</div> <div class="vers-content">Et tradidit ei medium exercitum, et elephantos: et mandavit ei de omnibus quæ volebat, et de inhabitantibus Judæam, et Jerusalem:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">34</div> <div class="vers-content">And he delivered to him half the army, and the elephants: and he gave him charge concerning all that he would have done, and concerning the inhabitants of Judea, and Jerusalem:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">34</div> <div class="vers-content">Half his army he entrusted to Lysias, and the elephants besides; and he signified all that he would have done, concerning Juda and Jerusalem particularly.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">35</div> <div class="vers-content">et ut mitteret ad eos exercitum ad conterendam et extirpandam virtutem Israël, et reliquias Jerusalem, et auferendam memoriam eorum de loco:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">35</div> <div class="vers-content">And that he should send an army against them, to destroy and root out the strength of Israel, and the remnant of Jerusalem, and to take away the memory of them from that place:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">35</div> <div class="vers-content">A force must be sent to overpower all that fought for Israel, or were yet left in Jerusalem, and make a clean riddance of them; no trace of these must be left;</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">36</div> <div class="vers-content">et ut constitueret habitatores filios alienigenas in omnibus finibus eorum, et sorte distribueret terram eorum.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">36</div> <div class="vers-content">And that he should settle strangers to dwell in all their coasts, and divide their land by lot.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">36</div> <div class="vers-content">all through the country settlers must be brought in from abroad, and the lands allotted between them.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">37</div> <div class="vers-content">Et rex assumpsit partem exercitus residui, et exivit ab Antiochia civitate regni sui anno centesimo et quadragesimo septimo: et transfretavit Euphraten flumen, et perambulabat superiores regiones.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">37</div> <div class="vers-content">So the king took the half of the army that remained, and went forth from Antioch the chief city of his kingdom, in the hundred and forty-seventh year: and he passed over the river Euphrates, and went through the higher countries.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">37</div> <div class="vers-content">With that, the king left his capital of Antioch, taking the remainder of his army with him; it was the hundred and forty-seventh year of the empire. Soon he was across Euphrates river, and on the march through the high countries.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">38</div> <div class="vers-content">Et elegit Lysias Ptolemæum filium Dorymini, et Nicanorem, et Gorgiam, viros potentes ex amicis regis:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">38</div> <div class="vers-content">Then Lysias chose Ptolemee the son of Dorymenus, and Nicanor, and Gorgias, mighty men of the king’s friends.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">38</div> <div class="vers-content">Three generals Lysias appointed for the task; Ptolemy son of Dorymenes, Nicanor and Gorgias, nobles all that were high in the royal favour;</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">39</div> <div class="vers-content">et misit cum eis quadraginta millia virorum, et septem millia equitum, ut venirent in terram Juda, et disperderent eam secundum verbum regis.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">39</div> <div class="vers-content">And he sent with them forty thousand men, and seven thousand horsemen: to go into the land of Juda, and to destroy it according to the king’s orders.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">39</div> <div class="vers-content">with forty thousand foot and seven thousand horse they were to march on Juda and make an end of it, as the king had ordered.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">40</div> <div class="vers-content">Et processerunt cum universa virtute sua, et venerunt, et applicuerunt Emmaum in terra campestri.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">40</div> <div class="vers-content">So they went forth with all their power, and came, and pitched near Emmaus in the plain country.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">40</div> <div class="vers-content">So out they went, with all this army at their back, marched in, and pitched their tents near Emmaus, down in the valley.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">41</div> <div class="vers-content">Et audierunt mercatores regionum nomen eorum: et acceperunt argentum, et aurum multum valde, et pueros, et venerunt in castra ut acciperent filios Israël in servos, et additi sunt ad eos exercitus Syriæ, et terræ alienigenarum.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">41</div> <div class="vers-content">And the merchants of the countries heard the fame of them: and they took silver and gold in abundance, and servants: and they came into the camp, to buy the children of Israel for slaves: and there were joined to them the forces of Syria, and of the land of the strangers.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">41</div> <div class="vers-content">Be sure the traders all about were apprised of their coming, and made their way into the camp with great sums of silver and gold, and a retinue of servants besides, thinking to buy Israelite slaves; levies, too, from Syria and Philistia made common cause with the invader.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">42</div> <div class="vers-content">Et vidit Judas et fratres ejus, quia multiplicata sunt mala, et exercitus applicabant ad fines eorum: et cognoverunt verba regis, quæ mandavit populo facere in interitum et consummationem:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">42</div> <div class="vers-content">And Judas and his brethren saw that evils were multiplied, and that the armies approached to their borders: and they knew the orders the king had given to destroy the people and utterly abolish them.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">42</div> <div class="vers-content">Judas, then, and his brethren found that matters had gone from bad to worse; here were the enemy encamped within their frontiers; they heard, besides, what orders the king had given for the destruction and taking away of their people.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">43</div> <div class="vers-content">et dixerunt unusquisque ad proximum suum: Erigamus dejectionem populi nostri, et pugnemus pro populo nostro, et sanctis nostris.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">43</div> <div class="vers-content">And they said every man to his neighbour: Let us raise up the low condition of our people, and let us fight for our people, and our sanctuary.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">43</div> <div class="vers-content">And the word went round among them, Now to restore the lost fortunes of our race; now to do battle for people of ours, sanctuary of ours!</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">44</div> <div class="vers-content">Et congregatus est conventus ut essent parati in prælium, et ut orarent et peterent misericordiam et miserationes.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">44</div> <div class="vers-content">And the assembly was gathered that they might be ready for battle: and that they might pray, and ask mercy and compassion.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">44</div> <div class="vers-content">So a general assembly was called; they must make ready for the fight, and pray besides, to win mercy and pardon.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">45</div> <div class="vers-content">Et Jerusalem non habitabatur, sed erat sicut desertum: non erat qui ingrederetur et egrederetur de natis ejus. Et sanctum conculcabatur: et filii alienigenarum erant in arce; ibi erat habitatio gentium: et ablata est voluptas a Jacob, et defecit ibi tibia et cithara.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">45</div> <div class="vers-content">Now Jerusalem was not inhabited, but was like a desert: there was none of her children that went in or out: and the sanctuary was trodden down: and the children of strangers were in the castle, there was the habitation of the Gentiles: and joy was taken away from Jacob, and the pipe and harp ceased there.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">45</div> <div class="vers-content">Not at Jerusalem; Jerusalem lay there, no city but a desert waste, nor any of her sons came and went; her sanctuary defiled, her citadel garrisoned by the alien, she was but a haunt of the Gentiles. Sad days for the men of Jacob; pipe nor harp sounded there now.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">46</div> <div class="vers-content">Et congregati sunt, et venerunt in Maspha contra Jerusalem, quia locus orationis erat in Maspha ante in Israël.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">46</div> <div class="vers-content">And they assembled together, and came to Maspha over against Jerusalem: for in Maspha was a place of prayer heretofore in Israel.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">46</div> <div class="vers-content">At Maspha, then, they gathered, looking across towards Jerusalem; time was when Maspha, too, had its place of prayer.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">47</div> <div class="vers-content">Et jejunaverunt illa die, et induerunt se ciliciis, et cinerem imposuerunt capiti suo, et disciderunt vestimenta sua:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">47</div> <div class="vers-content">And they fasted that day, and put on haircloth, and put ashes upon their heads: and they rent their garments:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">47</div> <div class="vers-content">All that day they fasted, and wore sackcloth, and covered their heads with ashes, and tore their garments about them.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">48</div> <div class="vers-content">et expanderunt libros legis, de quibus scrutabantur gentes similitudinem simulacrorum suorum:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">48</div> <div class="vers-content">And they laid open the books of the law, in which the Gentiles searched for the likeness of their idols:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">48</div> <div class="vers-content">What sights were these? Here, lying open, was a copy of the law, such as the heathen were ever making search for, … the counterpart of their own images. </div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">49</div> <div class="vers-content">et attulerunt ornamenta sacerdotalia, et primitias, et decimas: et suscitaverunt Nazaræos, qui impleverant dies,</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">49</div> <div class="vers-content">And they brought the priestly ornaments, and the firstfruits and tithes, and stirred up the Nazarites that had fulfilled their days:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">49</div> <div class="vers-content">Here they had brought priestly vestments, and offering of first-fruits and tithes; here Nazirites were gathered, ripe and ready for the payment of their vows.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">50</div> <div class="vers-content">et clamaverunt voce magna in cælum, dicentes: Quid faciemus istis, et quo eos ducemus?</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">50</div> <div class="vers-content">And they cried with a loud voice toward heaven, saying: What shall we do with these, and whither shall we carry them?</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">50</div> <div class="vers-content">And a loud cry rose to heaven, What shall we do for these, thy votaries? Whither escort them now?</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">51</div> <div class="vers-content">et sancta tua conculcata sunt, et contaminata sunt, et sacerdotes tui facti sunt in luctum, et in humilitatem:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">51</div> <div class="vers-content">For thy holies are trodden down, and are profaned, and thy priests are in mourning, and are brought low.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">51</div> <div class="vers-content">Sanctuary of thine is all profanation and defilement, priesthood of thine all misery and despair.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">52</div> <div class="vers-content">et ecce nationes convenerunt adversum nos ut nos disperdant: tu scis quæ cogitant in nos.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">52</div> <div class="vers-content">And behold the nations are come together against us to destroy us: thou knowest what they intend against us.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">52</div> <div class="vers-content">And now, see where the heathen muster their armies to destroy us! Needs not we should tell thee, how murderous their intent.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">53</div> <div class="vers-content">Quomodo poterimus subsistere ante faciem eorum, nisi tu, Deus, adjuves nos?</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">53</div> <div class="vers-content">How shall we be able to stand before their face, unless thou, O God, help us?</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">53</div> <div class="vers-content">Lord, but for thy aid, how shall we resist their onslaught?</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">54</div> <div class="vers-content">Et tubis exclamaverunt voce magna.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">54</div> <div class="vers-content">Then they sounded with trumpets, and cried out with a loud voice.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">54</div> <div class="vers-content">Loudly their voices, and loud the trumpets rang.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">55</div> <div class="vers-content">Et post hæc constituit Judas duces populi, tribunos, et centuriones, et pentacontarchos, et decuriones.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">55</div> <div class="vers-content">And after this Judas appointed captains over the people, over thousands, and over hundreds, and over fifties, and over tens.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">55</div> <div class="vers-content">Thereupon Judas chose out who should be their leaders, one with a thousand, one with a hundred, one with fifty, one with ten men to follow him;</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">56</div> <div class="vers-content">Et dixit his, qui ædificabant domos, et sponsabant uxores, et plantabant vineas, et formidolosis, ut redirent unusquisque in domum suam secundum legem.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">56</div> <div class="vers-content">And he said to them that were building houses, or had betrothed wives, or were planting vineyards, or were fearful, that they should return every man to his house, according to the law.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">56</div> <div class="vers-content">he sent home, too, all such as the law holds exempt; all that had but just built house, or married wife, or planted vineyard, and whoever had no stomach to the fight. </div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">57</div> <div class="vers-content">Et moverunt castra, et collocaverunt ad austrum Emmaum.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">57</div> <div class="vers-content">So they removed the camp, and pitched on the south side of Emmaus.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">57</div> <div class="vers-content">Then they moved camp, and pitched their tents southward of Emmaus.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">58</div> <div class="vers-content">Et ait Judas: Accingimini, et estote filii potentes, et estote parati in mane, ut pugnetis adversus nationes has quæ convenerunt adversus nos disperdere nos, et sancta nostra:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">58</div> <div class="vers-content">And Judas said: Gird yourselves, and be valiant men, and be ready against the morning, that you may fight with these nations that are assembled against us to destroy us and our sanctuary.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">58</div> <div class="vers-content">Now for girded loins, cried Judas, and brave hearts! By to-morrow’s light, you must engage yonder heathen, sworn enemies to us, and to the ground we hold sacred.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">59</div> <div class="vers-content">quoniam melius est nos mori in bello, quam videre mala gentis nostræ, et sanctorum.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">59</div> <div class="vers-content">For it is better for us to die in battle, than to see the evils of our nation, and of the holies:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">59</div> <div class="vers-content">Better die in battle, than live to see our race and our sanctuary overpowered.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">60</div> <div class="vers-content">Sicut autem fuerit voluntas in cælo, sic fiat.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">60</div> <div class="vers-content">Nevertheless as it shall be the will of God in heaven so be it done.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">60</div> <div class="vers-content">Be it what it may, heaven’s will be done!</div></div></td>
								</tr>					</tbody>
				</table>
			</div>
